# FUNERAL SEQUENCE BEGIN


>**_SUPER: THE FUNERAL_**<

A piano and organ accompany a congregation of voices singing VICTORY IN JESUS

INT. CHURCH - FLASHBACK

A Protestant church on Sunday morning.

We pan across the sea of white faces and find the only black face: MITCH. Standing beside his mother and singing along.

On the other side of JACKIE, Mitch’s father, OWEN stands awkwardly not singing but mouthing the words a few beat behind the melody.

MITCH & JACKIE
~ Oh, Victory in Jesus.
~ My savior forever.
~ He sought me and he bought me
~ With his redeeming blood--

PAPER STAND ATTENDANT (V.O.)
You buyin’ that or you just want to read it?

.SNAPBACK TO PRESENT

EXT. BROADWAY and SEVENTH - DAY

Mitch stares a moment at the open doors of FIRST BAPTIST CHURCH. The sounds of VICTORY IN JESUS can be heard coming from within.

Smiling from ear to ear, Mitch hands the PAPER STAND ATTENDANT a dollar and takes a copy.

REPORTER #1 (PRELAP)
I thought you said the print edition circulation was up.

Unfolding the front page, the full-page add on the back is for BELOVED OF GOD CHURCH with a PASTOR PIKE LEWIS WELCOMES YOU and a photo of the same man from the billboard.

DECK (PRELAP)
Circulation **is** up. Felix is very happy--hey Mitch, come join us.

INT. NASHVILLE TRIBUNE PRESSROOM - DAY

Mitch arrives in the middle of an impromptu meeting holding two fresh cups of coffee.

All in the pressroom are standing or have moved their roller chairs in a circle. Deck is leading. Mitch joins the circle, meeting-in-progress.

COPYWRITER #1
Felix is always happy when circulation is up.

Mitch slips the extra coffee he’s carrying to Darlita beside him with a wink. She eyes him suspiciously but takes the coffee anyway.

REPORTER #1
How many pages were in the special section?

DARLITA
(under her breath to Mitch)
Don’t think that makes up for taking my front page.

MITCH
(under his breath to Darlita)
They’re telling me they’ll be another one of those "front page" things tomorrow.

DARLITA
You get in my way again and ya might get run over.

They “clink” coffee cups with a sly smile.

DECK
Forty-eight.

REPORTER #2
How many were supposed to be about Jimmy?

DECK
Felix asked for Sixteen. 

Groans from everyone.

REPORTER #3
There’s no way we can fill that much content.

DECK
We have a double-page spread for the obit and memorial. 

COPYWRITER #1
Can we stretch that to four if we throw in some sponsored content?

REPORTER #1
Who in their right minds is going to sponsor paid content beside an obit?

SHANNON
“Ten tips for picking out a casket for your loved one”?

SHANNON HARTMAN (40’s, F, BLACK, Professional, MBA from somewhere Ivy League-adjacent, natural hair) offers to more groans, multiple eye-rolls.

DECK
I guess if we have to. Main thing is we just don’t have the writers to cover all those special section pages.

SHANNON
I pitched it to Felix earlier this morning and he loved the idea. Deck I want you to reach out to every sports stringer you’ve ever worked with, every high school athlete that has ever expressed an interest in Jimmy Chin and you get them to write something.

DECK
So that means we still have at least twelve pages to fill with stories about other team members.

REPORTER #1
Are there any other players on the team besides Jimmy?

Several chuckles.

DECK
FELIX! Nice of you to join us.

The mood shifts with the arrival of the “big boss.” FELIX (50’s, M, white, Suit & Tie, radiates “My lawyer could seriously mess you up” energy)

FELIX
Oh, I didn’t want to interrupt you, but now that I have let me tell you this: This paper made a big bet earlier this year--A big bet on the celebrity of a football player who is now, unfortunately, deceased. We prepared a complete ad campaign featuring the local celebrity and proud Vietnamese-American native son. All of it--gone in an instant. But then fortune smiled on us and gave us a gift in the person of mister Mitch Sawyer. 

All heads turn to Mitch like headlights hitting a deer.

MITCH
(whispers)
What is happening?

Darlita: eye-roll.

FELIX
Not only did he beat every network to the punch but he was a good twelve hours ahead of them. The numbers on Sunday are THROUGH THE ROOF. People all over the world want to know about Jimmy Chin. And we--oh yes--we want to tell them.

Spontaneous applause from his colleagues.

The “NEWS POPE”, having blessed his parishioners, returns to Vatican City on an upper floor of the building and the faithful disperse.

On his way out:

FELIX
Oh, Mitch, you and Deck: cover that funeral tonight. 

DECK
(glancing at MITCH)
Will do, sir.

Felix looks at Deck and Deck takes the hint and walks away.

FELIX
I called your Uncle Pike--

MITCH
Pike Lewis is not my uncle.

FELIX
I told Pike that I was really glad I gave you a shot here.

MITCH
(meaning it)  
I'm happy that you're happy.

FELIX
A few years go, Balthazar Getty and I were getting high in an opium den in Nepal and he said to me: “We’re all just minor characters in someone else’s movie.” I’ve never forgotten that.

MITCH
I know I never will.

FELIX
Good man.

Felix exit.

Deck approaches, somewhat jealous of the attention by the big boss.

MITCH
A funeral? How did they get the autopsy done so quickly?

DECK
The family is having a service for an empty casket. We’ll need to leave after lunch.

Deck returns walks back to his office and closes the door. On the back of the Door “DECK LAYTON, SPORTS EDITOR”.

Mitch turns around in the chair and faces a blank computer screen. Top-right corner of the screen is a clock that reads 

>_DEADLINE IN 6:32:03_<

While Mitch watches the minutes tick down to ‘6:31:00’ 

Mitch stares at the blank text document.

Mitch looks around the pressroom. Everyone is involved in their own deadlines.

Mitch notices the front page of the newspaper from the day the Titanic sank, framed on the wall. Beside that, the day Kennedy was shot, beside Pearl Harbor and the Moon Landing. Mitch stares at them.

Mitch stares at the blank computer screen. 6:30:32…1

Mitch picks up the phone and dials.

MITCH (prelap)
You get a cause of death?

INT. FARMERS MARKET - DAY

TOMMIE & MITCH both have wrapped sandwiches, walking toward a door to exit. Walk-n-talk:

TOMMIE
They're going to take me off this case.

TOMMIE has circles under her eyes. She hasn’t slept.

MITCH
What makes you say that?

TOMMIE
The case is too big. They're going to turn it into a task force. Updating the mayor and city council alone is a full-time job. The bottom line is: I need help.

MITCH
Autopsy... is it back?

TOMMIE
Prelim is Blood loss and trauma from multiple G.S.W. We’ll get the full report in a couple of days.

MITCH
Victimology?

TOMMIE
He had exactly three things he cared about: Football, His grades, and being Vietnamese. Nobody at the college will talk to me because I’m a cop and nobody in the Vietnamese community will talk to me because I’m black.

MITCH
And a cop.

TOMMIE
The football team won't talk to me. It's like they didn't even know him.

MITCH
Maybe they didn't.

TOMMIE
No hazing or late night parties?

MITCH
He was first-generation.

They exit to the patio.

EXT. FARMERS MARKET - PATIO - CONTINUOUS

TOMMIE
First of his family to go to college. 

MITCH
The pressure to not screw it up must have been intense.

They sit at a concrete table-with-umbrella, and unwrap their food.

TOMMIE
Nobody will even tell me if he had a girlfriend. There was no porn in his college apartment.

MITCH
A college apartment with no pornography: Maybe I should put that on the front page.

.MITCH'S NIKON

- A young couple steals a moment in the semi-private space behind the building--SNAP.

.PATIO AT FARMER'S MARKET

TOMMIE (O.S.)
You ever think he might be an asexual monk devoted to football the way you are to journalism?

MITCH
(sardonic)
He’s not an asexual monk--At least he doesn’t come to any of the meetings. Either way, why do police always assume the lover did it?

TOMMIE
Because what we love always ends up killing us.

She takes a bite of her cheesesteak sandwich.

EXT. NASHVILLE TRIBUNE - DAY

Finished with lunch, Mitch opens the glass door to go back inside the newspaper’s office building, when a low rumble grabs his attention. 

A BLACK DODGE CHALLENGER rolls up on the street and squeaks the tires. The tinted window rolls down; Deck is at the wheel.

DECK
Get in.

EXT. CANEYVILLE HIGH SCHOOL, CANEYVILLE, KY - FLASHBACK

A large scoreboard tells us this is the home of the CANEYVILLE HIGH SCHOOL BEARS--THE PRIDE OF CANEYVILLE, KENTUCKY.  

Coach stands with DECK on the sidelines of a high school football field holding a megaphone. They are watching the team practice O/C.

DECK
What's his name?

COACH
LEE.

DECK
Oriental?

COACH
Asian.

DECK
Chinese or Japanese?

COACH
Vietnamese.

Deck: Realizing that there’s a THIRD option.

Coach blows his whistle and they both clap for the O/C play.

COACH
(into the megaphone)
Reset. Hammer formation. On one.

DECK
He looks good. You sure he's a high-school sophomore?

COACH
Yep.

We hear “Ugs” and the heavy thud of human beings colliding.

DECK
He looks real good.

Deck glances at several men in ath-leisure outfits sitting in the nearly-empty stands watching practice.

DECK
Already attracting plenty of scouts.

COACH
Yep.

Coach blows his whistle.

COACH
(into the megaphone)
Offense: Reset. Defense: KILL THAT QUARTERBACK! Up the middle. On two.

We hear the scramble of the play O.S.--Everyone’s on the sideline’s head goes up watching the pass on the field.

MITCH (V.O.)
You knew him back then? 

INT./EXT. INTERSTATE 65 HEADED NORTH - PRESENT DAY

The BLACK DODGE CHALLENGER barrels down the interstate like Deck’s competing in a NASCAR race. They have to speak up to talk over the engine noise.

DECK
That was the first pass I saw him throw...

Deck downs a couple of aspirin with his free hand while keeping one hand on the wheel.

DECK
It was beautiful--seventy-five yards at least--straight as an arrow.

MITCH
You look like an undercover cop in this car.

Deck takes a coffee cup out of Mitch’s hand and takes a swig handing the cup back.

DECK
(pointing to his temple)
That’s why I never get pulled over. 

Deck passes on the left then right two more cars deemed unworthy of being in front of him. Mitch spot-checks door lock.

DECK
Hey, What would you think about some changes at the paper?

MITCH
What kind of changes?

Mitch sets the coffee cup in the dashboard cupholder without drinking any more.

DECK
Management changes. I’ve heard some rumors. The Overton family and Felix have always been--well, less than cordial.

Right then Deck dodges a car who honks in anger. They speed past a sign: “Welcome to Kentucky: The Bluegrass State”.

MITCH
Felix won’t sell.

DECK
He may not have a choice. Ad sales are down. And Felix--well, he clearly has an agenda.

MITCH
What ‘agenda’?

DECK
Hiring a bla--I mean, a woman as a senior editor instead of a more qualified internal candidate?

MITCH
You mean... you?

DECK
Yeah. Whatever. Ancient history. Felix bet all his chickens on Jimmy Chin Lee--special sections, the works.

MITCH
And then someone went and killed him.

DECK
And those chickens of his--they’re coming home to roost. Big time.

Another near miss--Squeaking tires and honking.

.MITCH'S NIKON

- Multiple gas stations with large news-vans gassing up: CNN, FOX SPORTS, Local ABC--SNAP

- A CRACKER BARREL with a full parking lot and a line out the door-SNAP.

- Traffic lined up to park at the church - SNAP

- A line of people out the door and across the parking lot being herded by uniformed police - SNAP

EXT. CANEYVILLE FIRST UNITED METHODIST CHURCH - LATE AFTERNOON

Deck parks the charger on the grass in the church overflow parking. The cars on either side of them have KENTUCKY license plates--Deck’s is Tennessee.

.MITCH'S NIKON

- A small group of people are holding signs that read “PASS HATE CRIME LEGISLATION”--FOCUS--SNAP

- A policeman is standing guiding the flow of mourners--SNAP

- Many people have on black suits and dark ties. Others are simply dressed casual--SNAP

- The audience is mostly Mayonnaise-American, From their dress, primarily blue-collar--SNAP

- A MOURNER IN A VANDY REPLICA JERSEY breaks down in tears--SNAP

- FRIENDS join REPLICA JERSEY and console each other--SNAP

- In the line of mourners waiting to get in: One WELL-DRESSED ASIAN LADY--ALEXIS MING--BLACK DRESS/DARK GLASSES--SNAP

- The perfect little black dress she’s wearing looks like it was made for her body--SNAP

- As the wind kicks up, the slit in her dress shows a little leg--SNAP 

- Alexis turns and a strand of hair falls across her face--SNAP

.PARKING LOT

Deck is scanning the crowd as Mitch notices a TOYOTA COROLLA with TENNESSEE PLATES: Davidson county. It has multiple parking stickers from VANDERBILT UNIVERSITY--some peeling off. 

Mitch fishes a business card out of his pocket, uses a pen to scratch his home number on the back, and puts it under the wiper blade.

Deck puts them on a path through the crowd that will get them as far away from the police line as possible, occasionally shaking hands with MOURNERS as if he knew them; Mitch follows in his wake.

INT. CANEYVILLE F.U.M.C. - SANCTUARY - CONTINUOUS

.MITCH'S NIKON

- The sanctuary is 100% “function over form”--SNAP

- Built in the 80's with standard-issue middle-class-white-evangelical-church pews and furniture--SNAP

- An OLDER ASIAN MAN in a black suit standing out in a sea of OLDER WHITE PEOPLE dressed in polyester-SNAP

- PIKE LEWIS (from the billboards) consoles JIMMY’S PARENTS - SNAP

- Mitch takes several photos of PIKE praying with Jimmy’s parents

- The only Asian person in the room, Alexis, notices Mitch taking photos, giving him shade.

ALEXIS
(under her breath)  
Perv.

- The camera loves her - SNAP 

.CHURCH SANCTUARY

A look of recognition passes between Deck and Alexis. Mitch misses it fiddling with his camera.

Organ music starts. First soft, then a little louder to let you know the service is beginning.

Near the back of the audience, MITCH spots TOMMIE trying not to look like a cop and failing miserably.

MITCH
Back in a sec

Mitch slides out of the pew and starts down the aisle toward Tommie in the back of the room.

From the stage, Pike Lewis takes notice of Mitch, then looks around trying to make sure nobody noticed him staring.

MITCH
(to Tommie)
Anything new?

TOMMIE
The mayor is introducing a task force in the morning.

MITCH
Who’s leading it?

The Music starts and Mitch sings along, knowing the words.

TOMMIE
The Hammer.

Mitch stops singing, more than a little bit alarmed. 

MITCH
Why are they--

TOMMIE
Guess?

MITCH
Pike Lewis?

TOMMIE
He called the Mayor and told her he would feel better if Barfield led the investigation.

Tommy scuffles off. Staring after her, Mitch then returns to his seat beside Deck and continues singing along with the hymns from memory, Head buzzing with what Tommy just told him.

Mitch glances at Alexis. 

When Mitch is not looking, Alexis watches Mitch sing.

EXT. CANEYVILLE FIRST UNITED METHODIST CHURCH - SUNSET

.MITCH'S NIKON

- A crowd of mourners--SNAP

- Walking from the church to an on-site cemetery where a black casket over an open grave waits--SNAP.

.GRAVESIDE - SUNSET

She wears dark glasses against the setting sun: Mitch again notices ALEXIS MING.

He tries to get closer to her but the crowd of mourners makes it difficult. 

The assembled begin to sing “Amazing Grace”. Mitch sings the baritone harmony line from memory. Alexis again, covertly watches him sing.

.MITCH's NIKON

- JIMMY'S PARENTS--**RUTH AND BOB LEE**--both white/anglo and looking close to retirement--are never far from Pike Lewis--SNAP

- Pike Lewis wipes away a tear--SNAP

- RUTH AND BOB LEE: each doesn’t know what to do with their hands - snap

- RUTH AND BOB LEE: Hands at their sides - snap

- Their hands inch together and the tips of the fingers find each other

- The way the older couple holds hands... almost covertly, like an apology for needing each other so much right now--SNAP

.GRAVESIDE - SUNSET

Deck joins Mitch and notices Alexis. Alexis wipes away tears from behind the glasses.

Sitting on the casket, a photo of Jimmy.

.MITCH'S NIKON

THE PARENTS purposely don't look at his photo. Then, when they’ve run out of directions, the photo causes Mom to enter the full-on-ugly-crying-meltdown stage.

.GRAVESIDE - SUNSET

Mitch seeing this, lowers his camera without taking a photo.

Everyone else can only stand awkwardly and watch as both mother and father console each other: They are in the crowd but completely alone in their grief.

We watch as Mitch takes in the silent dignity of the moment, letting his camera hang around his neck and bowing his head as the Pastor prays a benediction on Jimmy Chin Lee's life.

EXT. PARKING LOT, CANEYVILLE, KY - NIGHT

The sodium vapor lights of the parking lot attract insects and illuminate the thinning crowd. 

JIMMY’S MOM
He said God told him it would be better to wait another year.

Mitch is interviewing the parents, taking notes as they talk.

MITCH
“God” told him? He said that?

Mitch catches a glimpse of Deck interviewing his coach-friend. 

JIMMY’S DAD
He told us “Sometimes the loyalty we owe God comes before the loyalty we owe other people.”

That phrase catches Mitch’s attention.

Beyond Deck, Alexis catches Mitch’s eye as she walks to her car. Mitch watches her find his business card. 

MITCH
(Shaking the parents hand)
Thank you both very much for your time. I am very sorry for your loss.

Alexis gets in the COROLLA WITH TN PLATES and drives away. 

Mitch lifts his camera and gets a few shots before the car is out of sight.

## FUNERAL SEQUENCE END

===

